==Awards, records and milestones==
===Awards===
====Week/Month====
*[[Kevin Garnett]] was named [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] Player of the Week for games played from November 5 through November 11.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/pow_yao_garnett_071112.html?rss=true Garnett and Yao Named Players of the Week], ''[[NBA|NBA.com]]'', November 12, 2007.</ref>
*Head coach [[Doc Rivers]] was named Eastern Conference Coach of the Month for games played in October and November.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/celtics/news/rivers_com_071203.html Rivers Named Coach of the Month], ''[[NBA|NBA.com]]'', December 3, 2007.</ref>
*[[Paul Pierce]] was named Eastern Conference Player of the Week for games played from December 10 through December 16.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/pow_071217.html Roy, Pierce Named Players of the Week], ''[[NBA|NBA.com]]'', December 17, 2007.</ref>
*Paul Pierce was named Eastern Conference Player of the Week for games played from December 24 through December 30.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/playersoftheweek_071231.html Boston<U+2019>s Paul Pierce and New Orleans<U+2019> Chris Paul Named East and West Players of the Week], ''[[NBA|NBA.com]]'', December 31, 2007.</ref>
*Kevin Garnett was named Eastern Conference Player of the Week for games played from March 17 through March 23.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/pow_080324.html Kevin Garnett, Chris Paul Named Players of the Week], ''[[NBA|NBA.com]]'', March 24, 2008.</ref><ref>Greg Lee, [http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/extras/celtics_blog/2008/03/kg_pow.html KG P.O.W.], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', March 24, 2008.</ref>
*Head coach Doc Rivers was named Eastern Conference Coach of the Month for games played in March.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/coaches_080401.html Boston<U+2019>s Rivers, Utah<U+2019>s Sloan Named Coaches of the Month], ''[[NBA|NBA.com]]'', April 1, 2008.</ref>
*Kevin Garnett was named Eastern Conference Player of the Week for games played from April 7 through April 13.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/pow_080414.html Garnett, Iverson Named Players of the Week], ''[[NBA|NBA.com]]'', April 14, 2008.</ref>
*Head coach Doc Rivers was named Eastern Conference Coach of the Month for games played in April.<ref>[http://www.nba.com//coaches_080417.html Rivers, Jackson Named Coaches of the Month], ''[[NBA|NBA.com]]'', April 17, 2008.</ref>

====[[2008 NBA All-Star Game|All-Star]]====
*[[Doc Rivers]] and the Celtics coaching staff earned the honor of coaching the [[NBA All-Star Game|Eastern Conference All-Stars]] for the [[2008 NBA All-Star Game]] in [[New Orleans Hornets|New Orleans]] as a result of the [[Boston Celtics|Celtics]]' 109<U+2013>93 victory over the [[New York Knicks]] on January 21. The win guaranteed that the Celtics would have the best record in the [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] as of February 3, the cutoff date for the selection.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/rivers_as_080121.html Doc Rivers to Coach East in 2008 All-Star Game], [[NBA|NBA.com]], January 21, 2008.</ref>
*[[Kevin Garnett]] was voted as a starter for the 2008 NBA All-Star Game, leading all players in final votes received in the [[NBA All-Star Game|NBA All-Star]] Ballot with 2,399,148&nbsp;votes, the 6th highest total in NBA All-Star Balloting history.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/allstar2008/allstar_starters_080124.html Boston<U+2019>s Kevin Garnett Top Vote-Getter Among All-Stars], [[NBA|NBA.com]], January 24, 2008.</ref>
*[[Paul Pierce]] was named as a reserve for the 2008 NBA All-Star Game.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/allstar2008/reserves_080131.html Two Hometown Hornets Named as Reserves for 2008 NBA All-Star Game], [[NBA|NBA.com]], January 31, 2008.</ref>
*[[Ray Allen]] was named by NBA Commissioner [[David Stern]] to replace injured [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|East]] All-Star [[Caron Butler]] as a reserve for the 2008 NBA All-Star Game.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/allstar2008/Allen_Butler_080213.html Boston<U+2019>s Ray Allen to Replace Caron Butler in All-Star Game], [[NBA|NBA.com]], February 13, 2008.</ref>
*[[Rajon Rondo]] was named to participate in the [[T-Mobile]] [[Rookie Challenge|Rookie Challenge and Youth Jam]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/allstar2008/rookie_sophomore_080130.html Roy Headlines T-Mobile Rookie Challenge & Youth Jam], [[NBA|NBA.com]], January 30, 2008.</ref>

====Season====
*[[Kevin Garnett]] was named [[NBA Defensive Player of the Year Award|NBA Defensive Player of the Year]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/garnett_defensive_080422.html Kevin Garnett Wins Kia Defensive Player of the Year], ''[[NBA]].com'', April 22, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.nba.com/celtics/playoffs2008/press042208-garnett-defensive-player.html Kevin Garnett Wins NBA Defensive Player of the Year], ''[[Boston Celtics|Celtics]].com'', April 22, 2008.</ref><ref>Marc J. Spears, [http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/articles/2008/04/22/garnett_wins_nba_defensive_player_award/ Garnett wins NBA defensive player award], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', April 22, 2008.</ref>
*Kevin Garnett was named to the [[All-NBA Team|All-NBA First Team]].<ref name=allnba08>[http://www.nba.com/news/all_nba_080508.html MVP Kobe Bryant Highlights All-NBA First Team], ''[[NBA]].com'', May 8, 2008.</ref><ref name=allnbaglobe>Marc J. Spears, [http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/articles/2008/05/09/garnett_voted_to_nba_first_team/ Garnett voted to NBA first team], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', May 9, 2008.</ref>
*[[Paul Pierce]] was named to the [[All-NBA Team|All-NBA Third Team]].<ref name=allnba08/><ref name=allnbaglobe/>
*Kevin Garnett was named to the [[NBA All-Defensive Team|NBA All-Defensive First Team]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/defensive_team_080512.html Kobe, Garnett Headline All-Defensive Team], ''[[NBA]].com'', May 12, 2008.</ref>
*General manager [[Danny Ainge]] was named [[NBA Executive of the Year Award|NBA Executive of the Year]].<ref name=execyear>[http://www.nba.com/news/ainge_executive_080514.html Boston<U+2019>s Danny Ainge Named 2007-08 NBA Executive of the Year], ''[[NBA]].com'', May 14, 2008.</ref>
*Paul Pierce was named [[Bill Russell NBA Finals Most Valuable Player Award|NBA Finals Most Valuable Player]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/playoffs2008/news/story?id=3449953 Pierce wins MVP and big three take care of business in Finals], ''[[Associated Press]]'', June 18, 2008.</ref>

===Records===
====Season====
*[[Kevin Garnett]] joined a very short list of [[NBA]] players to record a 20 [[Point (basketball)|point]], 20 [[Rebound (basketball)|rebound]], 5 [[Assist (basketball)|assist]] game in their first night with a new team, with the others being [[Charles Barkley]], [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] and [[Maurice Stokes]], against the [[Washington Wizards]] on November 2.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=271102002 Garnett, Pierce spark Celtics' trampling of Wizards], ''[[Associated Press]]'', November 2, 2007.</ref>
*With an 8<U+2013>0 season start, the Celtics were off to their best opening since winning 10 in a row to start the [[1972-73 NBA season|1972-73 season]].<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=271114002 Celts put six players in double figures to improve to 7-0], ''[[Associated Press]]'', November 14, 2007.</ref>
*[[Kevin Garnett]]'s streak of 410 consecutive games with double figures in points came to an end as he scored only 8&nbsp;points in Boston's 104<U+2013>59 blowout victory<ref name="nyblowout">[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=271129002 Celtics end Knicks' brief winning streak with colossal romp], ''[[Associated Press]]'', November 29, 2007.</ref> over the [[New York Knicks]] on November 29, 2007. This was the longest streak among active players and is good for 7th in [[NBA]] history, with [[Michael Jordan]] holding the record with 840&nbsp;games.<ref>Peter Masucci, [http://wbztv.com/celtics/Boston.celtics.column.2.597002.html Banner 17: Tragic Tale Of Unfilled Potential], ''[[WBZ-TV|WBZ]]'', November 27, 2007.</ref>
*The Celtics marked their 6th biggest win in the history of the franchise and the biggest since a 153<U+2013>107 victory over the [[Washington Wizards|Baltimore Bullets]] in the [[1970-71 NBA season|1970-71 season]] with a 104-59 blowout victory over the [[New York Knicks]] on November 29, 2007. Their biggest win came against the [[Golden State Warriors|Philadelphia Warriors]] in the [[1961-62 NBA season|1961-62 season]] with a 153<U+2013>102 victory.<ref name="nyblowout"/>
*With a 12<U+2013>0 season start at home, the Celtics matched their 2nd best home opening since winning 12 in a row to start the [[1984<U+2013>85 NBA season|1984-85 season]]. Their best home opening came in the [[1957-58 NBA season|1957-58 season]], when they started the season with 17&nbsp;wins in a row.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/statistics/stats_week6_071210.html STATS: NBA Week 6 Notes], ''[[NBA|NBA.com]]'', December 10, 2007.</ref>
*The Celtics matched their longest winning streak since the [[1992-93 NBA season|1992-93 season]], when they won 9 in a row from March 16 to March 31, 1993, with a win against the [[Toronto Raptors]] on December 16.<ref name=streak9>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=271216028 Celtics match longest winning streak since 1993], ''[[Associated Press]]'', December 16, 2007.</ref>
*With a 20<U+2013>2 start, the Celtics matched the best start in franchise history. The only other team to achieve that record was the [[1963-64 NBA season|1963-64]] Celtics.<ref name=streak9/>
*With a 27<U+2013>3 start, the Celtics matched the best start through 30&nbsp;games in [[NBA]] history. One of the other 5 teams to accomplish that record was the [[1995-96 Chicago Bulls season|1995-96 Chicago Bulls]], who hold the [[NBA records|NBA record]] for most games won in a single season, with a record of 72<U+2013>10.<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280102002 Garnett, Celtics come out on top after battle with Rockets], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', January 2, 2008.</ref>
*Prior to their matchup on January 5, the Celtics and [[Detroit Pistons|Pistons]] combined for the 3rd highest [[winning percentage]] (.844) in the shot clock era after at least 30&nbsp;games.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280105008 Celtics rookie Davis scores 20 off bench to halt Pistons' 11-game streak], ''[[Associated Press]]'', January 5, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics matched their best start in the history of the franchise by reaching 30&nbsp;wins after only 34&nbsp;games.<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280111017 Garnett drops 20 as Celtics race to 30th win], ''[[Associated Press]]'', January 11, 2008.</ref>
*With a 34<U+2013>7 start, the Celtics matched their best record at mid-season in the history of the franchise. The other 3 teams to achieve that record were the [[1964-65 NBA season|1964-65]], [[1972-73 NBA season|1972-73]] and [[1984<U+2013>85 NBA season|1984-85]] Celtics.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280125002 Garnett's steal cements Celtics' last-second win over Timberwolves], ''[[Associated Press]]'', January 25, 2008.</ref>
*With a 16<U+2013>0 start against the [[Western Conference (NBA)|West]], the Celtics were off to the 2nd best opening against teams from the other conference in [[NBA]] history. The only other team to accomplish that record was the [[1971-72 Los Angeles Lakers season|1971-72 Los Angeles Lakers]], who won their first 19&nbsp;games against [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] teams.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280208016 Garnett can only watch as Powe's last-second layup lifts Celtics], ''[[Associated Press]]'', February 8, 2008.</ref>
*With 16&nbsp;assists against the [[Charlotte Bobcats]] on February 29, [[Rajon Rondo]] had the most assists in a game by a Celtics player since [[Sherman Douglas]] had 18 on March 1, 1995.<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280229002 Rondo's 16 assists power Celtics' close call vs. Bobcats], ''[[Associated Press]]'', February 29, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics won 10 straight games for the first time since the [[1985-86 NBA season|1985-86 season]], when they won 14 in a row from March 11 to April 4, 1986, with a win against the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] on March 12.<ref name=86team>[http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/basketball/celtics/view.bg?articleid=1079987 Win streak kicks up spirit of <U+2019>86], ''[[Boston Herald]]'', March 12, 2008.</ref><ref name=10straight>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280312002 Balanced Celtics rout Sonics for 10th straight victory], ''[[Associated Press]]'', March 12, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics swept the Texas Triangle,<ref>John Schuhmann, [http://www.nba.com/features/triangle_20080320.html Boston's trip through the Texas Triangle - Statement Made], ''[[NBA]].com'', March 21, 2008.</ref> consisting of the [[San Antonio Spurs]], [[Houston Rockets]] and [[Dallas Mavericks]], with a record of 3<U+2013>0 in consecutive road games from March 17 through March 20,<ref>Marc J. Spears, [http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/articles/2008/03/21/three_for_the_road/ Three for the road - Hustling Celtics pull off a rare triple in Texas], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', March 21, 2008.</ref> the first team to do it since the [[2001-02 Sacramento Kings season|2001-02 Sacramento Kings]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280320006 Celtics conclude Texas Triangle unmarked, hang on to outlast Mavs], ''[[Associated Press]]'', March 20, 2008.</ref> It was the 4th sweep in franchise history, and the first since the [[1986-87 Boston Celtics season|1986-87 season]].<ref>Marc J. Spears, [http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/dailydime?page=dime-080321 Boston Plays Texas Triangle As Few Have Before], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', March 21, 2008.</ref>
*With a 6<U+2013>0 record against the Texas Triangle, the Celtics were the 13th team in [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] history to sweep the season series against each of the three teams, doing it for the 5th time in franchise history,<ref name=texassweep>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/elias?date=20080320 Elias Says: Sports Statistics], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', March 20, 2008.</ref> and the first team since the [[1999-2000 NBA season|1999-2000]] [[Milwaukee Bucks]].<ref name=texassweep/>
*The Celtics defeated every team in the league at least once for the first time since the [[1990-91 NBA season|1990-91 season]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280328002 Pierce, Garnett combine to halt Hornet's 5-game streak], ''[[Associated Press]]'', March 28, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics broke the record for the best single-season turnaround in franchise history by improving from 24&nbsp;wins in [[2006-07 NBA season|2006-07]] to 66&nbsp;wins in [[2007-08 NBA season|2007-08]], a total of 42&nbsp;games.<ref>Mark Murphy, [http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/basketball/celtics/view.bg?articleid=1083604&srvc=celt&position=1 Celtics beat all comers - New Orleans last team to fall victim], ''[[Boston Herald]]'', March 29, 2008.</ref> The previous record of 32&nbsp;games was held by the [[1979-80 NBA season|1979-80]] Celtics, who improved from 29 to 61&nbsp;wins.<ref> Fran Blinebury, [http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/sports/5627752.html Celtics eye spoiler's role], ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'', March 18, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics broke the record for the best single-season turnaround in [[NBA]] history by improving from 24&nbsp;wins in [[2006-07 NBA season|2006-07]] to 66&nbsp;wins in [[2007-08 NBA season|2007-08]], a total of 42&nbsp;games.<ref name=heraldrecap37/> The previous record of 36&nbsp;games was held by the [[1997-98 San Antonio Spurs season|1997-98 San Antonio Spurs]], who improved from 20 to 56&nbsp;wins.<ref name=espnrecap37/><ref>Lisa Brooks, [http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/dailydime?page=dime-080403 Celtics: From Worst To First], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', April 2, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics set a franchise record for fewest free throws attempted and made, with 5 and 4.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280411002 Celtics pull starters in fourth, coast by Bucks], ''[[Associated Press]]'', April 11, 2008.</ref>
*With 3 [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] Player of the Week awards, [[Kevin Garnett]] has had the most such awards in a single season by a Celtics player since [[Larry Bird]] had 4 in the [[1985-86 NBA season|1985-86 season]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280414018 Big Three able to rest up as Celtics take care of Knicks], ''[[Associated Press]]'', April 14, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics sold out all 41 home games with an average attendance of 18,624 and set a single-season attendance record of 763,584.<ref>Marc J. Spears, [http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/articles/2008/10/06/good_business_model/ Good business model], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', October 6, 2008.</ref>

====Playoffs====
*[[Kevin Garnett]] has recorded a [[Double (basketball)#Double-double|double-double]] in 16 straight [[NBA Playoffs|playoff]] games dating back to the [[2004 NBA Playoffs|2004 Playoffs]]. [[Shaquille O'Neal]] is the only active player with longer such streaks, with 19 and 22.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/playoffs2008/stats_playoffs_080428.html STATS: NBA Playoffs: April 21 - 27], ''[[NBA]].com'', April 28, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics allowed a [[NBA Playoffs|playoff]] low in franchise history in opponent score in a half by holding the [[Atlanta Hawks]] to 26&nbsp;points in the first half of Game 7 in the First Round on May 4.<ref>[http://proxy.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280504002 Garnett's double-double propels Celts to second round], ''[[Associated Press]]'', May 4, 2008.</ref>
*[[Ray Allen]]'s streak of 852 consecutive games with points scored came to an end as he went scoreless in [[2008 NBA Playoffs#(1) Boston Celtics vs. (4) Cleveland Cavaliers|Game 1]] of the [[2008 NBA Playoffs|Conference Semifinals]] against the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] on May 6.<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280506002 Celtics duck Cavs despite lackluster game from Allen, Pierce], ''[[Associated Press]]'', May 6, 2008.</ref>
*[[Rajon Rondo]] was the first Celtics player to record at least 12&nbsp;assists twice in one postseason since [[Danny Ainge]] did it in the [[1988 NBA Playoffs|1988 Playoffs]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/elias?date=20080514 Elias Says... - Rondo's 13 assists], ''[[Elias Sports Bureau]]'', May 14, 2008.</ref>
*With 41 [[Point (basketball)|points]] in the [[2008 NBA Playoffs#Bracket|Conference Semifinals]] against the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] on May 18, [[Paul Pierce]] recorded the 2nd highest point total in franchise history in a [[Game seven|Game 7]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/celticsgame7scoring_080518.html Celtics Top Game 7 Scoring Performances], ''[[NBA]].com'', May 18, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280518002 Pierce, James duke it out as Celtics close out Cavs in Game 7], ''[[Associated Press]]'', May 18, 2008.</ref>
*[[Paul Pierce]] and [[LeBron James]] combined for the 2nd highest point total (86) in NBA history in a [[Game seven|Game 7]] on May 18.<ref>Brett Edgerton, [http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/dailydime?page=dime-080519 Two-Man Game], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', May 19, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics tied the record for the most consecutive road losses (6) in the [[NBA Playoffs|playoffs]] in NBA history with a loss in [[2008 NBA Playoffs#(1) Boston Celtics vs. (4) Cleveland Cavaliers|Game 6]] of the [[2008 NBA Playoffs#Bracket|Conference Semifinals]] against the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] on May 16.<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280524008 Garnett, balanced Celtics stun Pistons for first playoff road win], ''[[Associated Press]]'', May 24, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics were held to the 2nd fewest field goals (21) in an [[NBA Conference Finals|Conference Finals]] or [[NBA Finals]] game in the shot clock era in [[2008 NBA Playoffs#Conference Finals: (1) Boston Celtics vs. (2) Detroit Pistons|Game 4]] of the [[2008 NBA Playoffs#Bracket|Conference Finals]] against the [[Detroit Pistons]] on May 26.<ref>[[Elias Sports Bureau]], [http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/elias?date=20080526 Celtics Held to 21 Field Goals], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', May 26, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics became the 4th team in [[NBA]] history to be tied at 2<U+2013>2 in each of the first three [[NBA Playoffs|playoff series]].<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280526008 Celtics have trouble with shot as Pistons send series to Boston tied 2-2], ''[[Associated Press]]'', May 26, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics tied the record for the most home wins (12) in the [[NBA Playoffs|playoffs]] in NBA history with a win in [[2008 NBA Finals#Game 2|Game 2]] of the [[2008 NBA Finals|NBA Finals]] against the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] on June 8.<ref name=game2>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280608002 Celts withstand Lakers' late Game 2 run behind Pierce, defense], ''[[Associated Press]]'', June 8, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics broke the record for [[NBA Playoffs|playoff]] games (26) and home wins (13), and tied the record for most road losses (9) in a single postseason.<ref name=dailydime17/>

====[[2008 NBA Finals|Finals]]====
*With 21 [[Point (basketball)|points]] in [[2008 NBA Finals#Game 2|Game 2]] on June 8, [[Leon Powe]] recorded the 4th highest point total by a Celtic reserve since the [[1970 NBA Finals|1970 Finals]].<ref name=game2/>
*With 16 [[Assist (basketball)|assists]] in [[2008 NBA Finals#Game 2|Game 2]] on June 8, [[Rajon Rondo]] had the most assists in a [[NBA Finals|Finals]] game since [[Magic Johnson]] had 20 on June 20, 1991.<ref>[[Elias Sports Bureau]], [http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/elias?date=20080608 Team Work Pays Off], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', June 8, 2008.</ref>
*The Celtics recorded the 2nd best turnaround in [[NBA Finals|Finals]] history in a game after halftime since the [[1948 NBA Finals|1948 Finals]] after overcoming an 18-point deficit in [[2008 NBA Finals#Game 4|Game 4]] on June 12.<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280612013 Inspired Celtics storm back to push Lakers to brink of elimination], ''[[Associated Press]]'', June 12, 2008.</ref>
*[[Ray Allen]] was the first player to play all 48 minutes in an [[NBA Finals]] game since [[Jason Kidd]] did it in the [[2003 NBA Finals|2003 Finals]].<ref>[[Elias Sports Bureau]], [http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/elias?date=20080612 Complete game win for Ray Allen], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', June 12, 2008.</ref>
*With 38 points in [[2008 NBA Finals#Game 5|Game 5]] on June 15, [[Paul Pierce]] recorded the 3rd highest point total in franchise history in an [[NBA Finals]] game.<ref>[[Elias Sports Bureau]], [http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/elias?date=20080615 Pierce Scores 38 Points In Game Five], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', June 15, 2008.</ref>
*With 7 [[Three-point field goal|three-pointers]] in [[2008 NBA Finals#Game 6|Game 6]] on June 17, [[Ray Allen]] tied the record for three-pointers made in a [[NBA Finals]] game.<ref name=celtics17elias>[[Elias Sports Bureau]], [http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/elias?date=20080617 Elias Says...], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', June 17, 2008.</ref>
*With 22 [[Three-point field goal|three-pointers]], [[Ray Allen]] broke the record for three-pointers made in a [[NBA Finals]] series, eclipsing the previous record of 17 by [[Dan Majerle]] and [[Derek Harper]].<ref name=celtics17elias/>
*With 52 [[Three-point field goal|three-pointers]], the Celtics broke the record for three-pointers made in a [[NBA Finals]] series.<ref name=celtics17elias/>
*The Celtics became the 1st team to win an [[NBA Finals|NBA Championship]] after finishing with a winning percentage below .450 in the previous season since the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] did it in [[1976<U+2013>77 NBA season|1977]].<ref name=celtics17elias/>
*The Celtics became the 1st team to score at least 130 points in a [[NBA Finals]] game since the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] defeated the Celtics 141<U+2013>122 in the [[1987 NBA Finals|1987 Finals]].<ref name=celtics17elias/>
*[[Kevin Garnett]] became the 8th player to record a [[Double (basketball)#Double-double|double-double]] throughout a [[NBA Finals|Finals]] series, joining [[Bob Pettit]], [[Elgin Baylor]], [[Wilt Chamberlain]], [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], [[Bill Walton]], [[Moses Malone]] and [[Shaquille O'Neal]].<ref name=celtics17elias/>
*[[Kevin Garnett]] and [[Paul Pierce]] became the 2nd pair of teammates each to score 500 points in a single [[NBA Playoffs|postseason]], with 530 and 511 points, respectively.<ref name=celtics17elias/>
*With 39 points in [[2008 NBA Finals#Game 6|Game 6]] on June 17, the Celtics broke the record for largest margin of victory in a title clinching game, and 2nd largest margin in an [[NBA Finals]] game.<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280617002 Celtics smash Lakers, bring home 17th NBA championship], ''[[Associated Press]]'', June 17, 2008.</ref>
*With 17 [[Steal (basketball)|steals]] in [[2008 NBA Finals#Game 6|Game 6]] on June 17, the Celtics broke the record for steals in an [[NBA Finals]] game.<ref name=dailydime17>Chris Sheridan, [http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/dailydime?page=dime-080618 Title No. 17 Has A Familiar Smell For Celtics], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', June 17, 2008.</ref>

===Milestones===
*[[Paul Pierce]] moved up to 6th on Boston's all-time scoring list by passing [[Sam Jones (basketball)|Sam Jones]] with a [[layup]] in the third quarter against the [[Toronto Raptors]] on November 4.<ref name="pierceallenmilestones"/>
*[[Ray Allen]] passed 17,000&nbsp;[[Point (basketball)|points]] for his career with his first of two [[Three-point field goal|3-pointers]] in overtime against the [[Toronto Raptors]] on November 4.<ref name="pierceallenmilestones">[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=271104028 Allen's last-second 3 caps milestone day as C's nip Raps], ''[[Associated Press]]'', November 4, 2007.</ref>
*[[Paul Pierce]] became the 9th player in [[History of the Boston Celtics|Celtics history]] to play over 25,000&nbsp;minutes against the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] on November 23.<ref name="minutes">[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=271123002 Garnett gets double-double as Celtics coast to win over Lakers], ''[[Associated Press]]'', November 23, 2007.</ref>
*Ray Allen passed 30,000&nbsp;minutes for his career and became 103rd in minutes in [[NBA]] history against the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] on November 23.<ref name="minutes"/>
*Kevin Garnett moved up to 35th in points in NBA history by passing [[Walter Davis (basketball)|Walter Davis]] with a [[Jump shot (basketball)|jumper]] in the second quarter against the [[Sacramento Kings]] on December 26.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=271226023 Celtics begin first West Coast trip with victory over Kings], ''[[Associated Press]]'', December 26, 2007.</ref><ref name=nbapoints>[http://www.basketball-reference.com/leaders/pts_career.html Career Leaders and Records for Points], Basketball-Reference</ref>
*Kevin Garnett moved up to 26th in  [[Rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] in NBA history by passing [[Jack Sikma]] with a rebound in the second quarter against the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] on December 27.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280104002 Tony Allen's 20 help Celts past Grizzlies for eighth straight win], ''[[Associated Press]]'', January 4, 2008.</ref><ref name=nbarebounds>[http://www.basketball-reference.com/leaders/trb_career.html Career Leaders and Records for Total Rebounds], Basketball-Reference</ref>
*Ray Allen passed 2,000 [[three-point field goal]]s for his career with a 3-pointer in the fourth quarter against the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] on January 16.<ref>[http://www.basketball-reference.com/leaders/fg3_career.html Career Leaders and Records for 3-Pt Field Goals], Basketball-Reference</ref>
*Kevin Garnett moved up to 23rd in [[Block (basketball)|blocks]] in NBA history by passing [[Vlade Divac]] with a block in the second quarter against the [[Washington Wizards]] on January 12.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280118002 Celtics win second straight since losing streak], ''[[Associated Press]]'', January 18, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.basketball-reference.com/leaders/blk_career.html Career Leaders and Records for Blocks], Basketball-Reference</ref>
*Kevin Garnett passed 11,000&nbsp;rebounds for his career with a rebound in the fourth quarter against the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] on February 27.<ref>[http://www.kansascity.com/490/story/508719.html Recap: Boston vs. Cleveland], ''[[The Kansas City Star]]'', February 28, 2008.</ref>
*Kevin Garnett passed 20,000&nbsp;points for his career, becoming the 32nd player in [[NBA]] history to achieve that mark,<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/garnett20k_080307.html Kevin Garnett Reaches 20,000-Point Plateau], ''[[NBA]].com'', March 8, 2008.</ref> with a [[layup]] in the second quarter against the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] on March 8.<ref name="garnettray">Steve Bulpett, [http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/basketball/celtics/view.bg?articleid=1078957&srvc=celt&position=1 C<U+2019>s go extra milestone - Numbers come up for Garnett, Allen], ''[[Boston Herald]]'', March 9, 2008.</ref> The only other active players who have passed that mark are [[Shaquille O'Neal]], [[Allen Iverson]] and [[Kobe Bryant]].<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280308029 Allen, Celtics breeze by Grizzlies for eighth straight win], ''[[Associated Press]]'', March 8, 2008.</ref>
*Ray Allen passed 18,000&nbsp;points for his career with a [[Three-point field goal|3-pointer]] in the third quarter against the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] on March 8.<ref name="garnettray"/>
*Kevin Garnett moved up to 25th in  [[Rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] in NBA history by passing [[Bill Bridges (basketball)|Bill Bridges]] with a rebound in the third quarter against the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] on March 10.<ref name=86team/><ref name=nbarebounds/>
*Kevin Garnett moved up to 31st in points in NBA history by passing [[Tom Chambers (basketball)|Tom Chambers]] with a [[layup]] in the third quarter against the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] on March 12.<ref name=10straight/><ref name=nbapoints/>

